      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property Mid-Renovation: Incomplete Works, Half-Finished Bathrooms, and the Finish-or-Sell Decision
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        How to think about finishing versus selling as-is, what buyers actually pay for an unfinished project, and the disclosures and contract clauses that keep the deal clean.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>It is one of the most common conversations of the Brisbane renovation cycle. The owner is six months into a planned twelve-month project. The kitchen is half-done, the en-suite is gutted but not yet plastered, the back deck is framed but not yet decked, and circumstances have changed: the budget has run out, the relationship has changed, the job has moved interstate, the second mortgage repayment has become uncomfortable, or the original ambition has simply quietly cooled. The question becomes whether to push through and finish, or accept the position and sell mid-renovation.</p>

      <p>Both can be the right answer. The wrong answer, almost always, is to drift. A renovation that has paused without a decision tends to deteriorate quickly: the trades disperse, the protected materials get damaged, weather finds the unfinished sections, and what was a manageable interruption becomes a significant write-down. This article works through the finish-or-sell decision in a structured way, then sets out what selling mid-renovation actually looks like for Brisbane sellers: pricing, buyer pool, disclosure, contract structure, and the practical preparation that protects both the deal and the seller.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The finish-or-sell framework</h2>
      <p>Three numbers drive the decision. First, the cost remaining to finish to a defined finish line, with a credible builder quote rather than an optimistic estimate. Second, the time required to get there, including the trade availability lag that has already broken the original schedule. Third, the gap between the as-is sale price and the finished sale price, net of selling costs, capital gains, and the holding cost over the finish period.</p>

      <p>If the finished value is materially higher than the cost to complete plus the holding and risk cost, finishing is the right financial call, provided the seller has the budget, the appetite, and the project-management capacity to actually finish. If the finished value is only modestly higher, or if any of those three capacities is missing, selling as-is is usually the better answer.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Useful rule of thumb.</strong> Finishing makes sense when less than 25 percent of the renovation budget remains, the work is concentrated in trades that are available within four to six weeks, and the finish line is defined enough that scope creep is unlikely. Selling makes sense when major structural or services work remains, when approvals are unresolved, when the original budget has slipped by more than 30 percent, or when the seller's circumstances do not allow the focused project management a finish requires.</p>

      <p>The most common mistake is committing to a finish on the basis of optimistic numbers, then watching the budget overrun by another 20 to 40 percent and arriving at the listing date with the property still incomplete and the cash position worse. If the finish is happening, it needs to happen on the basis of a fixed-price builder contract, a clear finish line, and a budget the seller can fund without further stress.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually pay for an unfinished project</h2>
      <p>Buyers do not deduct the remaining build cost from the finished comparable price. They apply a multiplier, typically 1.3 to 1.6 times the cost to complete, to account for the time, risk, and effort of taking the project on. A property where $80,000 of work remains often trades $110,000 to $130,000 below a finished comparable. A property where $250,000 of work remains often trades $325,000 to $400,000 below.</p>

      <p>The multiplier is not arbitrary. It reflects the buyer's view that they will need to engage a builder under a new contract, accept a new schedule, fund the work themselves, accept the risk that hidden issues will surface once the existing work is opened up, and absorb their own time and stress. The buyers who are willing to take this on are a smaller pool: experienced renovators, builders, developers, or owner-occupiers with renovation experience and a tolerance for risk. The mass-market buyer who is looking for a finished home rarely engages.</p>

      <p>The multiplier compresses if the project is well-documented, the works are recent and well-executed, and the path to finish is clear. It expands if the works are stale, the documentation is thin, the trades have been irregular, or the approvals are uncertain. Sellers who invest in tightening the documentation and clarifying the finish path before listing typically narrow the multiplier from 1.6 toward 1.3.</p>

      <p>For more on what cosmetic and structural works are valued at by Brisbane buyers, see our notes on <a href="/insights/cosmetic-renovations-add-value-before-selling-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">cosmetic renovations and value before selling</a> and on <a href="/insights/should-i-renovate-before-selling-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">whether to renovate before selling</a>. For mid-renovation properties, the same principles apply, only sharper.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer pool and how to reach it</h2>
      <p>The mid-renovation buyer pool in inner-east Brisbane has three distinct sub-segments, and the campaign should be visibly targeted at all three. The first is the experienced renovator, who has done two or three projects, has a relationship with a builder, and is looking for a property where the previous owner has done the demolition and structural work. The second is a small builder or developer, who is looking to take the project on as a quick-turn refurbishment for resale. The third is an owner-occupier with renovation experience and a clear vision, often someone who has rented in the suburb for years and is prepared to live through the back end of the build.</p>

      <p>Each of these sub-segments responds to different signals. Experienced renovators want documentation: scope, costs to date, builder contacts, approvals, structural drawings, photographs of the works in progress. Small builders want clarity on time and cost: how soon could they start, how quickly could they finish, what is the realistic resale value. Owner-occupiers want reassurance and a vision: what does it look like when finished, can they live in part of the property during the works, what would the timeline be.</p>

      <p>A campaign that produces a clean information pack covering all three angles, that markets the property explicitly as a renovation opportunity rather than a finished home, and that uses photography that shows the existing work honestly rather than disguising it, performs significantly better than one that pretends the property is something it is not. The worst version is staged photos of unfinished rooms that look forced; the best version is honest, clear, well-lit images that show what has been done and what remains.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure and approval status</h2>
      <p>Queensland disclosure obligations bite hard on mid-renovation sales. The seller's solicitor will need to address whether the works are approved, partially approved, or unapproved; whether the approvals remain current or have lapsed; and whether QBCC-licensed builders or owner-builder permits are in play. A current approval that lapses before settlement creates a problem; an approval issued for a different scope than what is on the ground creates a bigger one.</p>

      <p>Sellers should expect a buyer's building and pest inspector to spend more time on a mid-renovation property than on a finished one. They will photograph the unfinished sections, comment on protective measures (or their absence), flag visible compliance issues, and sometimes recommend a structural engineer's review if any framing or load-bearing work has been altered. Their report will form the basis of the buyer's request for further information or for a price reduction.</p>

      <p>Active QBCC matters (a complaint, a directive, a dispute with a previous builder) need to be disclosed in writing. So do any handover certificates the seller has from completed trades, any warranty documentation, and any plans or approvals issued during the works. For unapproved structures, see our notes on <a href="/insights/selling-brisbane-property-unapproved-building-works" style="color:#f5d07a;">selling a Brisbane property with unapproved building works</a> and on <a href="/insights/unapproved-deck-pergola-carport-selling-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">unapproved decks, pergolas, and carports</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Contract structure and special conditions</h2>
      <p>Mid-renovation contracts often need special conditions to handle issues that finished-house contracts do not. Common ones include the following.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Vendor's warranty about works completed.</strong> A clause confirming that the works completed to date have been done in accordance with relevant approvals, by appropriately licensed trades where required, and to the seller's knowledge in compliance with the Building Code. This is reassurance to the buyer and a lever the buyer's solicitor will often request.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Treatment of materials on site.</strong> Whether tiles, fittings, joinery components, or other materials purchased for the project but not yet installed are included in the sale and at what value. These items are often a meaningful chunk of cost and they need to be addressed in the contract, not assumed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Existing builder contract and its assignment.</strong> If a current builder contract is in place, the contract should address whether the seller will terminate it, transfer it to the buyer with consent, or step away with a deed of release. Builder contracts are not automatically assignable; this needs structuring.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Approval transfer.</strong> If a current building approval is in place, the contract should address the timing of any required transfer of the certifier engagement to the buyer's name, and the practical handover of plans and stamped drawings.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance during the contract period.</strong> Properties under works carry different insurance requirements to finished homes. The contract should confirm who carries the risk during the contract period and confirm continuity of cover.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">No further works clause.</strong> A clause confirming the seller will not undertake further works between contract and settlement without the buyer's consent. Buyers do not want to inherit a different set of half-completed works to the one they inspected.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pre-listing preparation that pays</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Make safe and tidy.</strong> Even for a mid-renovation property, a tidy, well-lit, weatherproofed site presents far better than one with rubbish piles, exposed framing, and tarpaulins flapping. Spend a few hundred dollars on rubbish removal, basic site protection, and clean lighting. The same property looks 30 percent more confident.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Document the scope and cost to date.</strong> A one-page summary of what has been done, what remains, what has been spent, and what was originally budgeted. Buyers will read this and trust you more for having provided it. Hiding the data invites suspicion.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Get a builder's quote for completion.</strong> Even an indicative quote from a Brisbane inner-east builder is enormously useful for the buyer. It anchors the cost-to-complete number, prevents wild overestimation, and gives the buyer a starting contact for their own work.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Produce the design intent.</strong> If there are architect plans, builder drawings, or even mood boards, include them. Buyers want to see the vision, not just the half-built reality. The vision is part of what they are buying.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photograph honestly and well.</strong> Engage a photographer who has shot renovation projects before. Show the work in progress with good light. Do not stage rooms that are obviously unfinished, but do clean and protect them so they photograph cleanly.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brief your agent in detail.</strong> Your agent needs to be able to talk through the project in their sleep: what has been done, what remains, what the cost-to-complete looks like, what the finished value would be, what the approval status is, and what kind of buyer is the right fit. A briefed agent runs a confident campaign; an under-briefed agent loses the buyer at the third question.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing the campaign</h2>
      <p>The starting point is the finished comparable: what the property would sell for if the renovation were complete. Subtract a credible cost to complete, with the multiplier (1.3 to 1.6) applied. The result is the realistic top of the market for the property as it stands. Many sellers price above this number on the assumption that the right buyer will see the vision and pay closer to the finished value less only the bare cost to complete. That buyer is rare. Most buyers in this segment are pricing to make the project work for them, not for the seller.</p>

      <p>The pricing strategy is also affected by the seller's timeline. A seller with three months to settle does not have the luxury of holding out for the marginal buyer who might pay 5 percent more. A seller with twelve months to settle can be more patient. Be honest about which scenario you are in.</p>

      <p>Auction is rarely the right campaign structure for a mid-renovation property. The buyer pool is small, the buyers tend to be analytical rather than competitive, and the auction format does not suit a price discovery process where the buyer needs to model their own build cost. Private treaty with a guide price, or expressions of interest with a clear closing date, tend to work better. For the choice between formats, see our notes on <a href="/insights/auction-vs-private-treaty-eoi-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">auction vs private treaty vs expressions of interest</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When circumstances force the sale</h2>
      <p>Some sellers are not in a position to choose. Job loss, separation, illness, an interstate move, or a financial constraint can force the sale at the worst point in the project. The right response is to acknowledge the position, get good legal and agent advice early, and run a structured campaign rather than a panicked one. Buyers can read panic, and the discount they apply for it is significantly larger than the discount for a calm seller in a difficult position.</p>

      <p>If the seller is behind on mortgage payments or facing pressure from a lender, the sequencing of the sale, the mortgage discussion, and the contract becomes important. Our notes on <a href="/insights/behind-on-mortgage-considering-selling-options-before-default-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">selling before default</a> cover this case. The principles for a forced mid-renovation sale are the same, with the added complexity of an unfinished asset.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing checklist</h2>
      <p>1. Decide finish-or-sell on the basis of a credible builder quote, a defined finish line, and an honest read on capacity and budget. 2. If selling, make the site safe, tidy, and weatherproof. 3. Compile the scope-and-cost summary and the design intent documentation. 4. Get an indicative builder quote for the cost to complete. 5. Address all approval and QBCC matters with your solicitor before listing. 6. Engage a photographer experienced with renovation projects. 7. Brief your agent on every aspect of the project. 8. Set the price using a realistic multiplier on the cost to complete, not a hopeful one. 9. Choose a campaign structure that suits the analytical buyer pool. 10. Build a contract package that addresses materials, builder contracts, approvals, insurance, and the no-further-works position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Selling a Brisbane property mid-renovation is a recognisable scenario with a reasonably predictable buyer pool, a definable discount, and a workable contract structure. The sellers who handle it well treat it as a project of its own: structured, well-documented, honestly presented, and clearly priced. The sellers who handle it badly treat it as a problem to disguise, and the discount the buyer applies grows with every concealed detail. The decision to sell rather than finish is rarely the wrong one if it is taken decisively and prepared for properly. The decision to finish is rarely the wrong one if the budget, the time, and the project management capacity are genuinely there. The wrong decision, almost always, is to drift in between.</p>

